WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:03.000
Thanks, Sarah.

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:09.000
So today I'm going to be talking to you about this common romance trope.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:15.000
So to get into this, like any modern romance, you might end up on the dating apps.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:19.000
But since we're at PositConf, we're going to use TindR.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:25.000
So the reason I'm using Tinder is because I'm looking for a package to help me

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.000
with my very first package development journey.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.000
I've only been using R for about four years, and I'm an environmental engineer.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.000
So that means while I do use some data science and statistics,

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:43.000
it's not the main component of my job, so I don't identify as a real programmer.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:48.000
So getting into package development is a little bit daunting.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
So let's get to swiping and see what packages are out there.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:54.000
So the first one that comes up is Plumber.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.000
Plumber helps with web APIs and prototyping.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:01.000
And while that sounds really cool, I don't think that's going to help me

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:03.000
with my plan for what I'm going to develop.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:05.000
So I'm going to leave that on CRAN.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:09.000
But Purr, I know Purr. I love Purr.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:13.000
I'm definitely going to use the list mapping and functional programming

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:15.000
with some of my helper functions.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.000
So I'll go ahead and install that.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Now testthat, I don't really know what testthat is.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:22.000
Let's look into this.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:25.000
It catches mistakes and requires perfection.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:27.000
That sounds daunting.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.000
It sounds like something only real programmers would use.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:32.000
And I would prefer to leave that on CRAN,

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.000
because if any errors come up, I can Google it.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:38.000
I'm a perfectly capable programmer in that respect.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:42.000
But the thing is testthat comes highly recommended

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:47.000
by the package development book by Jenny and Hadley.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:50.000
And when a friend, or a friend of a friend of a friend,

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:54.000
recommends something, it can't hurt to give it a shot.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:56.000
So I'll go ahead and install this

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:59.000
and get to know testthat a little more.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:02.000
So testthat's been around for about 15 years,

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:05.000
and its job is to be a code tester.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:08.000
So you want to use this during package development

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:10.000
to test your code for specific conditions,

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:12.000
like warnings and errors,

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:18.000
or test for expected outputs, like specific numbers.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.000
The thing is, you're probably already doing testthat's job.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:25.000
So as an example, we're going to look into

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:29.000
what I've been developing for our package.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:30.000
This is Tidy Water.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.000
It's on CRAN if you want to check it out.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:35.000
And as an environmental engineer,

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.000
we work with drinking water treatment plants

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.000
to optimize their treatment processes

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:46.000
to provide better water quality to the general public.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
So this first function here, define water,

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:53.000
is what we start with for every single modeling scenario.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:55.000
And this creates a water.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.000
This is like making a cup of water

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:02.000
with specific parameters like pH, temperature, and alkalinity.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:07.000
I can then pipe my define water function into other models.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:09.000
So in this case, chem dose pH,

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.000
which calculates the pH and alkalinity

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.000
after we dose a chemical.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:16.000
So here we're dosing alum.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:19.000
We dose this at the beginning of most treatment processes

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:22.000
to coagulate out a bunch of dissolved material in the water

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:25.000
that you don't want to ingest.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.000
So if I want to test that this chem dose pH function

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.000
is operating as expected,

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.000
I might run this code chunk and then say,

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
what's my water at alkalinity?

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
And I can see that it's dropped from that 33 starting value

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:41.000
down to 17.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:45.000
But with testthat, all I have to do is wrap all of this code

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.000
in a testthat function,

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:49.000
label it so I remember what I'm testing.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
So test that chem dose pH returns the expected values,

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.000
and then replace that water alkalinity

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
with a testthat function like expect equal.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
And here I'm expecting that my calculation

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:08.000
from that code chunk equals a specific number, 17.87.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:11.000
So testthat seems kind of easy to use,

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:13.000
kind of interested so far.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:15.000
And if you're interested too,

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:17.000
you can get started at this QR code,

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:21.000
and that will take you to that package development book

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:25.000
by Jenny and Hadley, specifically to this testing basics.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.000
It's a little bit more involved

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:31.000
than just doing install packages, testthat.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
But you can go to this link,

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
and it'll tell you the exact steps to get through,

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
and it's not too difficult.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.000
So to get to know testthat a little bit more,

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:42.000
we're going to go on a few dates.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:45.000
So our first date will be a coffee date, super simple,

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.000
get to know testthat a little superficially.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:50.000
Then we'll go on a second date hike

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:53.000
where we start to trust testthat a little bit more.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:56.000
And finally, we're really going to commit to testthat

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
and get into a late relationship dinner with the parents.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:02.000
So this first date,

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:05.000
we're just going to test function inputs and outputs

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
and understand some of the functions

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:09.000
inside of the testthat package.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
So this first test is testing

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.000
that define water warns when no pH is input.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:19.000
So every water will have a pH,

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:21.000
and because of that,

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:24.000
all of our downstream models require pH.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
So if I don't include pH in my define water,

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:29.000
I should get a warning,

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:31.000
and the reason it's giving a warning

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:34.000
is because in my define water code,

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
I have this code that says,

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.000
if you're missing pH, throw a warning.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:41.000
But you can see I have a second warning on the bottom

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.000
if I'm missing alkalinity.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:45.000
So if I want to be really specific

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:47.000
and make sure that the correct warning being thrown

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:50.000
is related to pH, I can add some regex,

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.000
or I could add the entire warning message.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
Similarly, you can use expect error.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:59.000
In this case, I've entered pH as a character

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.000
instead of a number.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
So expect warning and expect error

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.000
are really useful for evaluating the outcomes

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:08.000
of your conditional statements.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:10.000
It's also useful for figuring out

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:15.000
when your user is breaking your code.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:20.000
Next we have testing that just define water works.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
So test.has a lot of really intuitive function names.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:27.000
So expect S3 class.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:30.000
Well, we expect the code inside of this function

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:32.000
to output an S3 class.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
You can also expect S4 class or an S7 class.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:38.000
You can also expect true.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:42.000
So here I'm saying my water pH should be a numeric.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.000
There's also an expect false function.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:49.000
And finally, there's this expect LT, expect less than.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:51.000
So my pH should be less than 14.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:53.000
Similarly, there's an expect GT,

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.000
which means expect greater than.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.000
So you can see these test that functions

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:59.000
are really intuitive, easy to understand

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:03.000
without even getting into the documentation too much.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.000
Finally, we have what I showed you earlier.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:07.000
You can write a whole chunk of code

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:09.000
inside of a test that function

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.000
and then evaluate the outputs from that code chunk.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.000
In this case, we're using expect equal again,

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.000
but you'll notice I've set that alkalinity to 200,

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:19.000
which is really high.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.000
So we should be getting an error.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:23.000
So we're going to take a little sidestep

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:27.000
into how testing is useful for error catching.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:31.000
So in your console, you can run DevTools test.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:33.000
And what this does is starts running

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.000
through all of your testing code.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:41.000
And what's going to show up is a yellow F for failure,

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
a pink W for warning, and an S for skipped.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:48.000
And in this left column, you can see the number of tests

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:51.000
that are run for each function you've developed.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.000
So I ran 33 tests for balanced ions,

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
25 tests for biofilters,

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:57.000
and every single one of those tests,

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:00.000
my team manually wrote.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:03.000
When it gets to the define water function at the end there,

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:06.000
it's run 50 tests, but one of them has failed.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
And it's gotten even more granular

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
and told me which test failed and why it failed.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:15.000
We expected that the calculation should be 200,

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
but my code was outputting 17.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
So this helps us isolate.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.000
If things go wrong, I don't need to manually

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.000
go through all of my code

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
to figure out where my error is.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
If I've written good tests,

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
I can go straight to this code

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:33.000
and understand what's going wrong.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:35.000
So this is pretty cool.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:37.000
What else can test that do?

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.000
So on a second date, we're going on this hike.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:41.000
We're trusting that it's not going to push us

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.000
off a cliff in the wilderness,

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:46.000
but rather look for obstacles

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
and prevent us from tripping over them.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
So as I mentioned earlier,

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
we always start with define water in our package,

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
creating that first cup of water.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
And into that cup of water,

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
I can dose chemical A and chemical B

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.000
and get a resulting pH and alkalinity.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:04.000
But there's another way I can get to this same answer.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:07.000
In one cup of water, I can dose chemical A.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:10.000
In a second cup of water, I can dose chemical B.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.000
I can mix them together using our blend waters function,

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:16.000
and I should get that same pH and alkalinity.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:19.000
So this shows how your package

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.000
can be really interconnected.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:24.000
And we really want our tests to fail.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
If something changes in that upstream function,

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
like chem dose pH,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
I want my blend waters to either reflect that change,

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
or if it doesn't, my test should fail.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:38.000
So what does this look like using test that?

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
So in this chunk of code,

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.000
we're going to test that this blend waters

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:45.000
handles our equilibrium chemistry correctly.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
So first, I make that starting water quality.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
I dose two chemicals into that first cup.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.000
Then I dose them separately and blend them

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:55.000
using blend waters.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
And then I expect that my pH using water B

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.000
should be the same as my pH from my blended waters.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:07.000
So this is a step up from testing hard-coded inputs.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.000
So instead of saying my pH should be 7,

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.000
why is it 7, what does 7 mean,

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
what else can I compare this to?

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
So this is really helping us

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:18.000
make our package more resilient

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:21.000
and account for the interconnectivity.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
So now that we know that tests

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:27.000
can catch hard-coded inputs like numbers,

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:30.000
it can test our conditional statements,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
it can test the interconnectivity,

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:35.000
we can really start to commit to test that

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:38.000
and see how far we can fall.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:41.000
So here we're in the late relationship stage.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:45.000
And we're just going to trust that our tests catch everything.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:48.000
In the example here, we're going to do a refactor.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:53.000
And refactoring is just changing your code

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
to maybe be more organized,

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:57.000
but your outputs shouldn't change.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:01.000
So this might mean changing your naming consistency

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
or adjusting your functions

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:06.000
to reflect the standards of Tidyverse.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:11.000
The detriment is that you could introduce bugs,

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
and hopefully your tests will catch that.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:17.000
In our case, we needed to really speed up our package.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
It was very slow when we were running thousands of scenarios.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
So to do this, we changed all of our functions

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
from Tidyverse functions to Base R.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:30.000
The thing is, our entire team learned R using Tidyverse,

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:33.000
so we're a little rusty on Base R.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:37.000
So you can imagine there's a lot of room for errors to sneak in.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:40.000
So as an example, we have this code chunk here

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.000
where I've highlighted the different Tidyverse functions

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
that we know and love.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
But when we change that to Base R,

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:51.000
suddenly there's three separate lines of code,

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:54.000
there's a lot of brackets and dollar signs.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.000
But the thing is, as I'm running this,

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:00.000
and I'm a little unsure about Base R,

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:03.000
I'll make sure that this works by running each line of code.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
And the thing is, it does.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
I don't run into any errors.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.000
The problem is, when I run my tests, I do get an error.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:15.000
And that's because this merge is replacing a left join.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:18.000
The merge default behavior is an inner join,

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
and to get that left join behavior,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.000
I need this allX equals true.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:26.000
So my tests were catching that I was dropping some data

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
that a left join would have kept

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:31.000
that this merge default was losing.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.000
So my point is that you can code,

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.000
you might not see an error,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:39.000
you might not account for edge cases

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.000
that your tests should catch.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:46.000
You might be lulled into a false sense of security as well

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:49.000
as you're coding that there's,

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:51.000
I don't need to run my tests, my code's working fine,

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.000
it's not breaking.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:57.000
And this is where you can add automated tests.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:59.000
So when you automate your tests,

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:02.000
you can write a Git workflow

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:06.000
that will execute on a push or pull request.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.000
For us, we have it set up such that

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
when you create a pull request,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
you cannot merge that pull request

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:18.000
until all of your tests and checks are passing.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.000
So down here, you can see there are two commits.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.000
One has a red X, one has a blue check mark.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:27.000
The red X means that some checks were not successful.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
This first red X is our command check.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:34.000
This is a very standard check for your code.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.000
In addition to running your tests

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
like we've been talking about,

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
it executes some checks.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:43.000
So it might check your documentation,

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:45.000
it checks that your dependencies are set up correctly,

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.000
and you need to pass this, our command check,

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.000
if you're planning on submitting to CRAN.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
And the second check that's failing is the test coverage,

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
and that's the equivalent of running

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.000
DevTools test in the console.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
If you are failing these tests,

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.000
you can click on the details link there,

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:06.000
and it'll take you right to where your code is failing.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
So similar to running DevTools test

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
or DevTools check in your console,

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:14.000
it's all here on GitHub and documented.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
The thing about tests is that

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.000
it's very frustrating sometimes.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.000
These are a bunch of commits that are failing.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.000
There's a lot of red Xs.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:27.000
This is where we finally get to that blue check mark.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:30.000
So if you start to implement tests,

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:33.000
you should know that it might take a lot of failure

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:35.000
before you see success,

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:39.000
but imagine doing this without tests.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
You might think you're fixing something

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:44.000
and break something else in the process of doing that.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
So your tests help you figure out

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:50.000
and make sure that your code is really robust.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
And this is where I started to feel

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
like a real programmer.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:58.000
I felt like our package was not built on a house of cards

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.000
where any change might crumble everything to ground.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
We can't add any new cool features

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.000
because it might break everything.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:12.000
So tests made us feel like it's very robust and very reliable.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:15.000
So my takeaways are that you should use test.that

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:18.000
at the beginning of package development

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:21.000
because your tests help you manage complexity

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:27.000
as you get your package more interconnected and complicated.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:30.000
It's easier to build coverage as you go

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:33.000
and a little harder to reverse engineer that later.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.000
You might miss out on those different edge cases.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:39.000
And building tests into your package

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:42.000
allows you to focus on cool development opportunities.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:46.000
For us, that meant being able to speed up our package significantly

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.000
by refactoring without having to worry too much

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:51.000
about the consequences.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.000
For you, it might look like an open-source project

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.000
where you can crowdsource cool ideas and contributions

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:01.000
from people who aren't as familiar with the intricacies of your package

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:05.000
and not worry about how they might break your package.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:07.000
Your tests should catch that.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:12.000
So overall, I was wrong to judge test.that so harshly.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
Luckily, we committed to the package early

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.000
and developed a really positive relationship

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:21.000
with test.that and with package development.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:25.000
So I'm hoping that if you're considering your first package

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.000
or you're in the early stages of developing a package,

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
that you too can find love with test.that

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:33.000
and start to feel like more of a real programmer.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.000
Thank you.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
Thank you.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:48.000
We have time for one question. There it goes.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.000
Have you found yourself writing code differently

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:55.000
once you've started implementing tests?

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:58.000
I don't know about writing code differently,

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
but I do notice that every time I test my code,

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:04.000
I run over and document it with a test.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:05.000
Yeah.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:09.000
Okay, maybe another question.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:13.000
What is your advice about when to write tests?

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.000
Just as you develop.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:19.000
So as you're writing your code and you're doing those typical tests

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:21.000
like, did this output why I expected it to?

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:22.000
Go write a test for that.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.000
If you have conditional statements where you have a bunch of if-else,

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:29.000
evaluate every single one of those and make sure they work.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:33.000
For us, we had a bunch of different chemicals we can add to each function,

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:38.000
so we want to make sure each chemical is behaving with the expected chemistry.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:41.000
Yeah, so make sure you're as covered as possible.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
Okay.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:46.000
One more quick question.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:50.000
What was the most difficult thing to learn about test that?

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:59.000
I think it was really difficult just to get into the mindset of using tests.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:02.000
When we first started, our project lead was like,

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.000
if you're writing a function, everyone's writing their own tests.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:07.000
I'm like, what does that mean?

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:08.000
That sounds so intimidating.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
That sounds like extra work.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:13.000
But once you do a couple tests, you realize that's actually really easy.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:15.000
I'm already doing this.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:16.000
Great.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:17.000
Thank you.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:18.000
Thanks.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:19.000
Okay.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:21.000
Thank you.

